izona|Prescott Valley]]\n#Our Lady of Guadalupe Church, [[Queen Creek, Arizona|Queen Creek]]\n#St. John Vianney Church, [[Sedona, Arizona|Sedona]]\n#St. Mary Mediatrix Mission, [[Yarnell, Arizona|Yarnell]]\n\n===Coconino County===\n#San Francisco de Asis, [[Flagstaff, Arizona|Flagstaff]]\n#Nativity of the Blessed Virgin Mary Chapel, Flagstaff\n#St. Pius X Center, Flagstaff\n#Our Lady of Guadalupe Chapel, Flagstaff\n#Holy Trinity Newman Center, Flagstaff [[Northern Arizona University|NAU]]\n#El Cristo Rey Mission, [[Grand Canyon Village, Arizona|Grand Canyon Village]]\n#[[Chapel of the Holy Cross (Sedona, Arizona)|Chapel of the Holy Cross]], [[Sedona, Arizona|Sedona]]\n#St. Francis Church, [[Seligman, Arizona|Seligman]]\n#St. Joseph Church, [[Williams, Arizona|Williams]]\n\n===Mohave County===\n#St. Margaret Mary Church, [[Bullhead City, Arizona|Bullhead City]]\n#Our Lady of the Desert Mission, [[Dolan Springs, Arizona|Dolan Springs]]\n#Our Lady of the Lake Church, [[Lake Havasu City, Arizona|Lake Havasu City]]\n#La Santisima Trinidad Mission, [[Littlefield, Arizona|Littlefield]] and [[Scenic, Arizona|Scenic]]\n#St. Mary Church, [[Kingman, Arizona|Kingman]]\n\n==Eastern Catholic Churches and Communities active in the area of the Diocese of Phoenix==\n\n# Holy Protection of Mary [[Byzantine Catholic Eparchy of Phoenix]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eparchyofphoenix.org |title=Home |publisher=Eparchy of Phoenix |date= |accessdate=2014-04-01}}</ref>\n# [[St Stephen Byzantine Catholic Cathedral]] in Phoenix<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ststephenbyzantine.org |title=St Stephen Byzantine Cathedral &#124; The Cathedral of the Holy Protection of Mary Byzantine Catholic Eparchy of Phoenix |publisher=Ststephenbyzantine.org |accessdate=2014-04-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120430202217/http://www.ststephenbyzantine.org/ |archivedate=2012-04-30 }}</ref>\n# [[St. Thomas the Apostle Byzantine Catholic Church]] in Gilbert<ref>[http://www.eparchyofphoenix.org/directory-of-parishes ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110815183654/http://www.eparchyofphoenix.org/directory-of-parishes |date=August 15, 2011 }}</ref>\n# [[Mar Auraha Chaldean and Assyrian Catholic Church]] in Scottsdale<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kaldu.org/2_st_peter_diocese/churches/mar_auraha.htm |title=Mar Auraha Chaldean Church |publisher=Kaldu.org |date= |accessdate=2014-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marauraha.com |title=MarAuraha.com! |publisher=MarAuraha.com! |date= |accessdate=2014-04-01}}</ref>\n# [[St. Joseph Maronite Catholic Church]] in Phoenix<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stjosephaz.org |title=Saint Joseph Maronite Catholic Church Arizona Celebrating Mass According to the Maronite Catholic Rite |publisher=Stjosephaz.org |date= |accessdate=2014-04-01}}</ref>\n# [[St. John of the Desert Melkite Catholic Church]] in Phoenix<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stjohnofthedesert.com |title=Home |publisher=Stjohnofthedesert.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-01}}</ref>\n# [[Dormition of the Mother of God Ukrainian Catholic Church]] in Phoenix<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukrainianchurch.org |title=Dormition of the Mother of God |publisher=Ukrainianchurch.org |date= |accessdate=2014-04-01}}</ref>\n# [[Syro Malabar Catholic Mission]] in Phoenix\n\n== Education ==\nThere are seven Catholic high-schools within the Diocese of Phoenix, 29 elementary schools, and 29 pre-schools.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dphx.org/about/|title=About the Diocese|publisher=Diocese of Phoenix}}</ref> \n[[Benedictine University]] and the [[University of Mary]] offer degree programs within the Diocese of Phoenix, and the diocese operates campus ministry programs at Newman Centers for four public universities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dphx.org/catholic-schools-universities/catholic-colleges-in-phoenix/|title=Catholic Colleges in Phoenix|publisher=Diocese of Phoenix}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nThe diocese uses several types of media to fulfill its evangelization efforts:\n\n===Radio ministry===\n\nRadio Family Rosary is a radio ministry of the Diocese of Phoenix founded in 1983. The station begins with a recitation of the [[rosary]] every day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radiofamilyrosary.com/radiofamilyrosary.html|title=Radio Family Rosary|accessdate=April 23, 2008|publisher=Radio Family Rosary|year=2008|author=Radio Family Rosary|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511143515/http://www.radiofamilyrosary.com/radiofamilyrosary.html|archive-date=May 11, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> After the rosary the station focus on a particular saint, or a point of catechism is held.  The station was founded by Dorothy Westfall, after a suggestion from a Phoenix parishioner suffering from [[arthritis]].<ref name=\"radio2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicsun.org/2006/oct19/media/radiorosary.html|title=The Catholic Sun Newspaper- Group provides rosary, catechism on AM radio|accessdate=April 23, 2008|publisher=The Catholic Sun Newspaper|year=2007|author=Andrew Junker|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720211523/http://www.catholicsun.org/2006/oct19/media/radiorosary.html|archive-date=July 20, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nBishop Thomas Olmsted often uses radio communication and has a website with information about his \"bishop's hour.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thebishopshour.org/|title=Catholic Podcasts - The Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix|website=thebishopshour.org}}</ref> on [[Immaculate Heart Radio]].\n\nThe diocese began financially supporting En Familia radio [[KIDR]] in 2012 to reach out to those who speak Spanish.\n\n=== Newspaper ===\n\n''[[The Catholic Sun]]'' is the official newspaper of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix.<ref name=\"ABOUT US1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicsun.org/aboutus.html|title=Mission Statement|accessdate=April 23, 2008|publisher=The Catholic Sun Newspaper|year=2008|author=The Catholic Sun Newspaper|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080423013957/http://www.catholicsun.org/aboutus.html|archive-date=2008-04-23|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nThe paper is delivered to more than 115,000 homes in the counties of [[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]], [[Maricopa County, Arizona|Maricopa]], [[Mohave County, Arizona|Mohave]],  and [[Yavapai County, Arizona|Yavapai]].<ref name=\"advertising\">{{cite web |url=http://www.catholicsun.org/advertising.html |title=ADVERTISING |accessdate=April 23, 2008 |publisher=The Catholic Sun Newspaper |year=2008 |author=The Catholic Sun Newspaper |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514201626/http://www.catholicsun.org/advertising.html |archive-date=2008-05-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Television ===\n\nMass is broadcast live from [[Cathedral of Saints Simon and Jude]] each Sunday morning by [[KAZT]], along with a show immediately following entitled \"Catholics Matter\". The Mass was once on [[KUTP]].<ref name=\"TV MASS MINISTRY\">{{cite web |url=http://www.diocesephoenix.org/events/index.html |title=Upcoming Events |accessdate=April 24, 2008 |publisher=Diocese of Phoenix |year=2008 |author=Diocese of Phoenix |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412212948/http://www.diocesephoenix.org/events/index.html |archive-date=April 12, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Social media===\nThe diocese has an active presence on YouTube, Flickr, Facebook, Twitter and others and continues to expand its presence online.\n\n==Religious orders active in the diocese==\nAs of 2020, twenty-eight communities of religious men and fifty communities of religious women have a presence in the Diocese of Phoenix.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dphx.org/consecrated-life/communities-religious-men/|title=Communities of religious men|publisher=Diocese of Phoenix}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dphx.org/consecrated-life/communities-of-religious-women/|title=Communities of religious women|publisher=Diocese of Phoenix}}</ref> A diocesan Office for Consecrated Life serves as a guide for members of religious communities and for persons interested in consecrated life in its various forms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dphx.org/consecrated-life/|title=Office for Consecrated Life|publisher=Diocese of Phoenix}}</ref>\n\n==Other Catholic organizations in the Diocese of Phoenix==\nThis list is fairly complete, but there might be others to add.\n* [[Andre House]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andrehouse.org|title=Andr\u00e9 House of Arizona \u2013 A House of Hospitality|website=www.andrehouse.org}}</ref>\n* [[Arizona Catholic]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arizonacatholic.org|title=Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix, Arizona - 2018 - The Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix|website=www.arizonacatholic.org}}</ref>\n* [[Arizona Catholic Conference]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120331122523/http://69.50.197.44/acc/]</ref>\n* [[Arizona Rosary Celebration]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rosarysunday.org|title=DOMAIN ERROR|website=rosarysunday.org}}</ref>\n* [[Beginning Experience]] Arizona Chapter<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.azbe.org/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-09-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003055223/http://www.azbe.org/ |archive-date=2011-10-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Catholic Cemeteries and Mortuaries]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholiccemeteriesphx.com |title=Catholic Cemeteries and Funeral Homes :: Diocese of Phoenix |publisher=Catholiccemeteriesphx.com |date= |accessdate=2018-07-25}}</ref>\n* [[Catholic Commerce Networking Association of Arizona]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ccnaaz.org/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-08-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807131349/http://ccnaaz.org/ |archive-date=2011-08-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Catholic Community Foundation]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccfphx.org|title=Catholic Community Foundation, Phoenix, AZ|publisher=}}</ref>  In November 2011, the Catholic Community Foundation of Phoenix announced that it was giving [[Thomas J. O'Brien (bishop)|former Bishop Thomas J. O'Brien]] its faith honoree award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/members/Blog/EJMontini/148981|title=azcentral.com - members|website=www.azcentral.com}}</ref>  When news of the intended award became public, there was outrage that the Foundation would honor a bishop who had resigned in disgrace, had admitted involvement in the sexual abuse scandal, and who had been convicted of the felony of hit-and-run involving death.  A few days later, O'Brien declined the award, and Foundation, stating that it did not anticipate the adverse public reaction, issued a formal written apology to the community.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/news/articles/2011/11/23/20111123bishop-obrien-forgoes-catholic-award.html|title=Former Bishop Thomas O'Brien forgoes Catholic award|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Catholic Charities Community Services]] \n* [[Catholic Charities Parish and Community Engagement]] /ParishCommunityEngagement.aspx\n* [[Catholic Committee on Scouting]] http://www.phxdccs.org/\n* [[Catholic Education Arizona]], formerly known as [[Catholic Tuition Organization of the Diocese of Phoenix]] http://www.ctodp.org/, http://www.catholiceducationarizona.org/\n* [[Catholic Engaged Encounter]] of Arizona, http://www.arizonacee.org/\n* [[Catholic Mens Fellowship Phoenix]] http://www.cmfp.org/\n* [[Catholic Physicians Guild of Phoenix]]  http://cpgphoenix.com/\n* [[Catholic Renewal Ministries of Phoenix]]  https://web.archive.org/web/20081120032340/http://crm-phoenix.communityspice.com/content\n* [[Catholic Singles Ministry]] http://www.catholicsinglesministry.org\n* [[Cursillo Movement]] in Phoenix http://phoenixcursillo.com/\n* [[Diocese of Phoenix Department of Medical Ethics]], https://web.archive.org/web/20110827174744/http://www.staphx.org/ethics_site/\n* [[Diocese of Phoenix Office of Natural Family Planning]], http://www.phxnfp.org/\n* [[Filipino Catholic Community of Arizona]], http://www.fccaz.com/\n* [[Foundation for Senior Living]] http://www.fsl.org/\n* [[Franciscan Renewal Center]] http://www.thecasa.org/\n* [[Immaculate Heart Radio]]  http://ihradio.com/stations/arizona-stations/phoenix-az-1310-am/\n* [[Italian Catholic Federation]] http://www.icf.org/\n* [[John Paul II Resource Center for the Theology of the Body]]  http://69.50.197.44/mfrl/jp2.html{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} \n* [[Kino Institute]] for Catholic Adult Faith Formation and Leadership, http://www.kinoinstitute.org/\n* [[Knights of Columbus]] Arizona State Council http://www.azknightsofcolumbus.com/\n* [[Korean Catholic Community of Phoenix]], https://web.archive.org/web/20110923002253/http://www.phoenixkoreancatholic.org/\n* [[Legatus]] of Phoenix,  http://www.legatus.org/chapter/phoenix\n* [[Legion of Mary]] of the Diocese of Phoenix, https://legionofmaryphoenix.com/\n* [[Life Teen]] for Catholic Teens http://www.lifeteen.com/\n* [[Living Waters Retreat Center]], Cornville http://www.livingwaterretreatcenter.com/\n* [[Pax Christi]] is active in several locations in the diocese\n* [[Mount Claret Retreat Center]] http://mtclaret.org/\n* [[Phoenix Diocesan Council of Catholic Women]] http://pdccw.com/\n* [[Radio Family Rosary]], http://www.radiofamilyrosary.com/\n* [[St. Joseph's Youth Camp]] http://www.sjycaz.com/\n* [[St. Joseph the Worker]] job service http://www.sjwjobs.org/\n* [[St. Mary's Food Bank Alliance]],  http://www.firstfoodbank.org\n* [[St. Thomas More Society]] of Phoenix, http://stthomasmorephoenix.grou.ps/\n* [[St. Vincent de Paul Society]], Phoenix http://www.stvincentdepaul.net/\n* [[Serra International]] apostolate for vocations, Phoenix Serra Club https://web.archive.org/web/20110923002510/http://www.phoenixserraclub.org/\n* [[Tepeyac Life Teen Camp]], [[Life Teen]], https://web.archive.org/web/20111117025418/http://www.lifeteencamps.com/tepeyac.asp\n* [[World Apostolate of Fatima]]  http://www.wafusa.org/\n* [[Worldwide Marriage Encounter]] Arizona Chapter http://www.wwme-phx.org/\n* [[Youth Arise North America]]  http://www.youtharise.org\n\n==Events since 2000==\nIn 2009 the Diocese contributed $50,000 to the successful campaign by Stand For Marriage Maine to overturn an impending legalization of same-sex civil marriage in Maine.<ref>{{cite news | title =Dioceses major contributors to repeal same-sex marriage | first = Chuck | last = Colbert | url = http://ncronline.org/news/politics/dioceses-major-contributors-repeal-same-sex-marriage | newspaper = [[National Catholic Reporter]] | location = Kansas City, Mo. | date = November 25, 2009 | accessdate =November 29, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mainecampaignfinance.com/public/entity_financial_transactions.asp?TYPE=BQC&ID=4528|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120911203857/http://www.mainecampaignfinance.com/public/entity_financial_transactions.asp?TYPE=BQC&ID=4528|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-09-11|title=Maine Campaign Finance contributions}}</ref>\n\nOn June 11, 2014, the diocese was \"stunned and deeply saddened\" at an attack on two priests during a burglary at Mater Misericordiae Mission in Phoenix. Parochial vicar Rev. Kenneth Walker, [[Priestly Fraternity of St. Peter|FSSP]], 28, ordained a priest just two years, was fatally shot. Rev. Joseph Terra, [[Priestly Fraternity of St. Peter|FSSP]], was wounded.<ref name=\"PriestKilled\">{{cite news|title=28-year-old priest killed in Phoenix church burglary|url=http://www.phoenixherald.com/index.php/sid/222852679/scat/caf48823f1822eb3/ht/28-year-old-priest-killed-in-Phoenix-church-burglary|accessdate=June 12, 2014|publisher=Phoenix Herald}}</ref>\n\nOn August 4, 2017, it was announced that a civil lawsuit was filed against [[Thomas J. O'Brien (bishop)|Thomas J. O'Brien]], who served as Bishop of the Catholic Diocese of Phoenix between the years 1982 to 2003,<ref name=\"o'Brinava\">https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/arizona/articles/2017-08-03/ex-catholic-bishop-of-phoenix-accused-of-sex-abuse-of-boy</ref> O'Brien is accused of sexually molested a boy on several occasions at parishes in Phoenix and Goodyear from 1977 to 1982.<ref name=\"o'Brinava\" /> O'Brien died on August 26, 2018, following complications from Parkinson's Disease.<ref>http://www.catholicsun.org/2018/08/27/bishop-thomas-j-obrien-retired-bishop-of-phoenix-dies-at-82/</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Joseph J. Henn, a former priest, was extradited from Italy to face charges of molestation in Phoenix. He had been laicized and expelled from the [[Salvatorian]] order in 2006.<ref name=phoenixdefrocking>https://cruxnow.com/church-in-europe/2019/05/31/former-priest-wanted-on-abuse-charges-in-arizona-arrested-in-italy/</ref><ref>https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/phoenix/2019/06/15/ex-priest-joseph-john-henn-returned-az-italy-child-molestation-charges/1467366001/</ref>\n\nOn February 25, 2020, indicted Diocese of Phoenix priest Thomas Spaulding, who was accused of sexually abusing at least two boys in Maricopa County, died awaiting trial.<ref name=spaulding>https://www.azfamily.com/news/phoenix-priest-indicted-on-child-sex-abuse-charges-dead-at/article_e0dc7102-58c6-11ea-9840-5fc30cb13a9c.html</ref><ref name=azcentralspaulding /> Spaulding, who was 75 years old when he died, was charged in January 2020 with six counts of sexual misconduct and one charge of child molestatation.<ref name=spaulding /><ref name=azcentralspaulding>https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/phoenix/2020/02/26/roman-catholic-diocese-phoenix-mesa-priest-john-jack-spaulding-dies-child-sex-crimes/4883112002/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Catholicism}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Catholic Church by country]]\n* [[Catholic Church in the United States]]\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States#Ecclesiastical province of Santa Fe|Ecclesiastical Province of Santa Fe]]\n* [[Global organisation of the Catholic Church]]\n* [[Life Teen]]\n* [[List of Roman Catholic archdioceses]] (by country and continent)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (alphabetical)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (structured view)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States]]\n{{div col end}}\n<!-- please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://dphx.org/ Official site]\n** [https://dphx.org/parishes/ List of parishes]\n** [https://dphx.org/about/related-organizations/ Other Catholic Organizations in the Diocese of Phoenix]\n** [https://dphx.org/bishop-olmsteds-coat-of-arms/ Coat of arms of the bishop and of the diocese]\n** [https://dphx.org/youth-protection/ Office for Child and Youth Protection]\n* [https://www.azcatholicconference.org/ Arizona Catholic Conference]\n* [http://www.thebishopshour.org/ \"Bishop's Hour\" radio program]\n* [http://www.catholiccharitiesaz.org/  Catholic Charities Community Services Arizona]\n* [http://www.catholicsun.org/ \"The Catholic Sun\" newspaper]\n* [http://www.catholicschoolsphx.com/ Catholic Schools of the Diocese of Phoenix]\n* [[United States Conference of Catholic Bishops]]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Santa Fe}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roman Catholic Diocese Of Phoenix}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in the United States|Phoenix]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Santa Fe|Phoenix]]\n[[Category:Catholic Church in Arizona|Diocese of Phoenix]]\n[[Category:Culture of Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in 1969]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 20th century|Phoenix]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Phoenix\n| latin             = Dioecesis Phoenicensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the Spanish language -->Di\u00f3cesis de Phoenix\n| image             = Phoenix - Cath\u00e9drale Saints-Simon-et-Jude - 2.jpg\n| image_size        = 250px\n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = Cathedral of Saints Simon and Jude\n| coat              = CoA Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix.svg\n| coat_size         = 150px\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = [[United States]]\n| territory         = [[Arizona counties]] of [[Maricopa County, Arizona|Maricopa]], [[Mohave County, Arizona|Mohave]], [[Yavapai County, Arizona|Yavapai]], and [[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]] (excluding the territorial boundaries of the [[Navajo Nation]]), and also includes the [[Gila River Indian Reservation]] in [[Pinal County, Arizona|Pinal County]]\n| province          = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Santa Fe|Santa Fe]]\n| coordinates       = {{coord |33|27|0|N| 112|4|0|W|}}<!-- Use {{coord}} -->\n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_sqmi         = 43,967\n| population        = 5,006,478\n| population_as_of  = 2019\n| catholics         = 1,225,677\n| catholics_percent = 24.5%\n| deaneries         = 7\n| parishes          = 94 & 23 missions\n| churches          = 117\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = 36\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| particular_church = [[Latin Church]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = December 2, 1969 ({{age|1969|12|2}} years ago)\n| cathedral         = [[Cathedral of Saints Simon and Jude]]\n| cocathedral       = \n| patron            = [[Our Lady of Guadalupe]]\n| priests           = 136\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop            = [[Thomas Olmsted|Thomas James Olmsted]]\n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = [[Eduardo Nevares|Eduardo Alanis Nevares]]\n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = \n| metro_archbishop  = [[John Charles Wester]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Diocese of Phoenix Map.png\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = Diocese of Phoenix, [[Arizona]]\n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [https://dphx.org dphx.org]\n| footnotes         =\n\n[[File:Virgen de guadalupe2.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Our Lady of Guadalupe is the patron saint of the Diocese]]\n|flag=|metropolitan=|headquarters=|sui_iuris_church=|founded=|dissolved=|language=}}\n\n{{coord |33|27|0|N| 112|4|0|W| display=title}}\nThe '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix'''  ({{lang-la|Dioecesis Phoenicensis}}, {{lang-es|Di\u00f3cesis de Phoenix}}) in [[Arizona]] is a [[particular church]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]] in the United States. It was established on December 2, 1969 when it was split off from the [[Diocese of Tucson]]. Its ecclesiastic territory includes [[Maricopa County, Arizona|Maricopa]], [[Mohave County, Arizona|Mohave]], [[Yavapai County, Arizona|Yavapai]], and [[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]] counties (excluding the territorial boundaries of the [[Navajo Nation]]), and also includes the [[Gila River Indian Reservation]] in [[Pinal County, Arizona|Pinal County]].<ref name=\"History of the Diocese\">{{cite web| last=''Diocese of Phoenix''| title=History of the Diocese| year=2008| url=http://www.diocesephoenix.org/dioceseInfo/history.htm| accessdate=2008-12-08| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080923114305/http://www.diocesephoenix.org/dioceseInfo/history.htm| archivedate=2008-09-23}}</ref> The [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|bishop]] is [[Thomas Olmsted]].\n\n==Early missions==\nJesuit priests began to work in northern Mexico in the 1610s in the lowlands near the coast. Originally, these missionaries worked out a peaceful compromise with the people of the [[Yaqui River]] valley allowing for the establishment of more than fifty mission settlements. This broke down when the Jesuits opposed the native [[shaman]]ic religious tradition. The [[Opata people]] were more receptive to the missionaries and allied with them. After this, the Jesuits began to move into [[Pima people|Pima]] and [[Tohono O'odham]] territories in present-day Arizona.<ref name=\"hamnett105\">{{cite book |title= Concise History of Mexico|url= https://archive.org/details/concisehistoryof0000hamn|url-access= registration|last= Hamnett |first=Brian R |year=1999 |publisher= Cambridge University Press |location=Port Chester, NY, USA |isbn= 978-0-521-58916-1 |page=[https://archive.org/details/concisehistoryof0000hamn/page/105 105]}}</ref> Spanish exploration and missionary work was sufficient to consider the territory part of [[New Spain]]. An agreement between General Pedro de Perea and the [[viceroy]] of New Spain resulted in the general shaping of the province, initially called ''Nueva Navarra'' in 1637, but renamed ''Sonora'' in 1648.<ref name=\"rincones37\">{{cite book |editor1-first=Victor Manuel |editor1-last=Jimenez Gonzalez |title=Sonora: Gu\u00eda para descubrir los encantos del estado |trans-title=Sonora: Guide to discover the charms of the state |year=2010 |publisher=Editorial Oc\u00e9ano de Mexico SA de CV |location=Mexico City |language=Spanish |isbn=978-607-400-319-2}}</ref>\n\nThe most famous missionary of what is now the [[Southwestern United States|American Southwest]] was [[Eusebio Kino]].<ref name=\"turhistoria\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sonoraturismo.gob.mx/conoce-sonora/historia-de-sonora/ |title=Historia de Sonora |publisher=Government of Sonora |location=Sonora Mexico |language=Spanish |trans-title=History of Sonora |accessdate=February 15, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202081817/http://www.sonoraturismo.gob.mx/conoce-sonora/historia-de-sonora/ |archivedate=February 2, 2011 }}</ref> He arrived in the province of ''Nueva Navarra'' in 1687 and started missionary work in the [[Pimer\u00eda Alta]] area. He began his first mission at Cucurpe, then established churches and missions in other villages such as [[Spanish missions in the Sonoran Desert|Los Remedios, Imuris, Magdalena, Coc\u00f3spera, San Ignacio, Tubutama and Caborca]]. To develop an economy for the natives, Father Kino also taught them European farming techniques.<ref name=\"enchistoria\">{{cite web |url=http://www.e-local.gob.mx/wb2/ELOCAL/EMM_sonora |title= Historia |year=2010 |work= Enciclopedia de Los Municipios y Delegaciones de M\u00e9xico Estado de Sonora |publisher= Instituto para el Federalismo y el Desarrollo Municipal |location=Mexico |language=Spanish |trans-title=History |accessdate=February 15, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"rincones38\">{{cite book |editor1-first=Victor Manuel |editor1-last=Jimenez Gonzalez |title=Sonora: Gu\u00eda para descubrir los encantos del estado |trans-title=Sonora: Guide to discover the charms of the state |year=2010 |publisher=Editorial Oc\u00e9ano de Mexico SA de CV |location=Mexico City |language=Spanish |isbn=978-607-400-319-2|page=38}}</ref>\n\n==Coat of arms==\nThe official description found in an earlier version of the website of the diocese read as follows: \"These arms are composed of a blue field on which is placed a silver (white) mountain to represent Camelback Mountain, a significant aspect of the backdrop of the See City. Arising from the mountain as a gold (yellow) bird that is coming forth from red flames to represent the mythological phoenix, that arose from the ashes, and for which the See City of Phoenix is named. Above the phoenix is a gold \"cross formy fitch\u00e9e (three arms of a cross and one resembling a spike), which is taken from the arms of the Diocese of Tucson to signify that it was from the territory of Tucson that the Diocese of Phoenix was carved in 1969.\" <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://old.diocesephoenix.org/bishop/olmstedCoatDownload.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-09-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324142919/http://old.diocesephoenix.org/bishop/olmstedCoatDownload.htm |archive-date=2012-03-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Bishops ==\nThe list of bishops of the diocese and their tenure of service:<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Catholic-hierarchy|diocese|dphoe|Diocese of Phoenix|21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.diocesephoenix.org/dioceseInfo/bishops.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2007-04-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070403231123/http://www.diocesephoenix.org/dioceseInfo/bishops.htm |archive-date=2007-04-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Bishops of Phoenix===\n# [[Edward Anthony McCarthy]] (1969\u20131976), appointed Coadjutor Archbishop and later [[Archdiocese of Miami|Archbishop of Miami]]\n# [[James Steven Rausch]] (1977\u20131981)\n# [[Thomas J. O'Brien (bishop)|Thomas Joseph O'Brien]] (1982\u20132003)\n# [[Thomas J. Olmsted|Thomas James Olmsted]] (2003\u2013present) \n\n===Auxiliary Bishop===\n* [[Eduardo Nevares|Eduardo Alanis Nevares]] (2010\u2013present)\n\n===Other priest of this diocese who became Bishop===\n* [[James S. Wall|James Sean Wall]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Gallup|Bishop of Gallup]] in 2009\n\n==Historically important churches==\n* [[Cathedral of Saints Simon and Jude]], [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]\n* [[St. Mary's Basilica, Phoenix]]\n* [[Immaculate Heart of Mary Church, Phoenix]]\n\n==Statistics==\n\nAccording to 2019 data from the diocesan web site, the Diocese of Phoenix reported these statistics:\n\n* Estimated Catholic Individuals.....1,225,677\n* Estimated Catholic Households....296,652\n* Diocesan Priests (including retired, sick, or absent).....138\n* Extern Priests.....78\n* Religious Priests.....93\n* Permanent Deacons.....222\n* Religious Brothers.....7\n* Religious Sisters.....134\n* Seminarians.....40\n* Parishes.....94\n* Missions.....23\n* Catholic Cemeteries.....6\n* Catholic Funeral Homes.....2\n* High Schools (Diocesan and Private)...7\n* Elementary Schools.......29\n* Pre-Schools..........29\n\n== Parishes and missions ==\n[[File:Phoenix-Scared Heart Church.jpg|200px|thumb|'''Sacred Heart Church''' built in 1900, is located in 920 S. 17th St. Phoenix, Arizona. It was added to '''National Register of Historic Places''' March 20, 2012. Reference number 12000124]][[File:Phoenix-St. Mary's Catholic Church-1915.jpg|200px|thumb|'''Saint Mary's Basilica''' was built in 1914 and is located at 231 N. 3rd. St. It was listed in the '''National Register of Historic Places''' on November 29, 1978, ref. #78000551.]][[File:Phoenix-Immaculate Heart of Mary.JPG|200px|thumb|'''Immaculate Heart of Mary Catholic Church''', built in 1928, is Phoenix's oldest Hispanic church. It is located at 909 E. Washington St.. It was listed in the '''National Register of Historic Places''' on October 8, 1993, ref. number 93000742]]\n\n* Parishes Map in Google<ref>{{cite web|url=http://g.co/maps/bmw8 |title=Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix - Google Maps |publisher=G.co |date= |accessdate=2014-04-01}}</ref>\n* Parish Directory<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diocesephoenix.org/parishes.php|title=Parishes - The Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix|website=www.diocesephoenix.org}}</ref>\n* List of Parishes by [[Deanery]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.diocesephoenix.org/deaneries.php |title=Deaneries - The Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix |publisher=Diocesephoenix.org |accessdate=2014-04-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407061754/http://www.diocesephoenix.org/deaneries.php |archive-date=2014-04-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Native American Missions<ref name=\"diocesephoenix1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.diocesephoenix.org/native-american-ministry.php |title=Native American Ministry - The Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix |publisher=Diocesephoenix.org |date= |accessdate=2014-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===Maricopa County===\n#Our Lady of Guadalupe Mission, [[Aguila, Arizona|Aguila]]\n#St. Rose Philippine Duchesne Church, [[Anthem, Arizona|Anthem]]\n#St. Thomas Aquinas Church, [[Avondale, Arizona|Avondale]]\n#St. Philip Benizi Mission, [[Black Canyon City, Arizona|Black Canyon City]]\n#St. Henry Church, [[Buckeye, Arizona|Buckeye]]\n#Our Lady of Joy Church, [[Carefree, Arizona|Carefree]]\n#St. William Church, [[Cashion, Arizona|Cashion]]\n#St. Gabriel the Archangel, [[Cave Creek, Arizona|Cave Creek]]\n#St. Andrew the Apostle Church, [[Chandler, Arizona|Chandler]]\n#St. Mary Church, Chandler\n#St. Columba Kim Korean Church, Chandler\n#Santa Teresita Church, [[El Mirage, Arizona|El Mirage]]\n#Ascension Church, [[Fountain Hills, Arizona|Fountain Hills]]\n#St. Michael Mission, [[Gila Bend, Arizona|Gila Bend]]\n#St. Anne Church, [[Gilbert, Arizona|Gilbert]]\n#St. Mary Magdalene Church, Gilbert\n#Our Lady of Perpetual Help Church, [[Glendale, Arizona|Glendale]]\n#St. Helen Church, Glendale\n#St. James Church, Glendale\n#St. Louis the King Church, Glendale\n#St. Raphael Church, Glendale\n#St. Thomas More Church, Glendale\n#St. John Vianney Church, [[Goodyear, Arizona|Goodyear]]\n#Our Lady of Guadalupe Church, [[Guadalupe, Arizona|Guadalupe]]\n#St. John the Baptist Church, [[Komatke, Arizona|Komatke]] [[Gila River Indian Community]] Mission<ref name=\"diocesephoenix1\"/>\n#All Saints Church, [[Mesa, Arizona|Mesa]]\n#Christ the King Church, Mesa\n#Holy Cross Church, Mesa\n#Queen of Peace Church, Mesa\n#St. Bridget Church, Mesa\n#St. Timothy Church, Mesa\n#All Saints Catholic Newman Center, Tempe [[Arizona State University|ASU]]\n#Good Shepherd Mission, [[New River, Arizona|New River]]\n#St. Charles Borromeo Church, [[Peoria, Arizona|Peoria]]\n#'''[[Cathedral of Saints Simon and Jude]]''', [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]\n#Corpus Christi Church, Phoenix\n#Holy Family Church, Phoenix\n#Immaculate Heart of Mary Church, Phoenix\n#Most Holy Trinity Church, Phoenix\n#Our Lady of Czestochowa Polish Church, Phoenix\n#Our Lady of the Valley Church, Phoenix\n#Sacred Heart Church, Phoenix\n#St. Agnes Church, Phoenix\n#St. Anthony Church, Phoenix\n#St. Augustine Church, P