in Mary Chapel, Flagstaff\n#St. Pius X Center, Flagstaff\n#Our Lady of Guadalupe Chapel, Flagstaff\n#Holy Trinity Newman Center, Flagstaff [[Northern Arizona University|NAU]]\n#El Cristo Rey Mission, [[Grand Canyon Village, Arizona|Grand Canyon Village]]\n#[[Chapel of the Holy Cross (Sedona, Arizona)|Chapel of the Holy Cross]], [[Sedona, Arizona|Sedona]]\n#St. Francis Church, [[Seligman, Arizona|Seligman]]\n#St. Joseph Church, [[Williams, Arizona|Williams]]\n\n===Mohave County===\n#St. Margaret Mary Church, [[Bullhead City, Arizona|Bullhead City]]\n#Our Lady of the Desert Mission, [[Dolan Springs, Arizona|Dolan Springs]]\n#Our Lady of the Lake Church, [[Lake Havasu City, Arizona|Lake Havasu City]]\n#La Santisima Trinidad Mission, [[Littlefield, Arizona|Littlefield]] and [[Scenic, Arizona|Scenic]]\n#St. Mary Church, [[Kingman, Arizona|Kingman]]\n\n==Eastern Catholic Churches and Communities active in the area of the Diocese of Phoenix==\n\n# Holy Protection of Mary [[Byzantine Catholic Eparchy of Phoenix]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eparchyofphoenix.org |title=Home |publisher=Eparchy of Phoenix |date= |accessdate=2014-04-01}}</ref>\n# [[St Stephen Byzantine Catholic Cathedral]] in Phoenix<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ststephenbyzantine.org |title=St Stephen Byzantine Cathedral &#124; The Cathedral of the Holy Protection of Mary Byzantine Catholic Eparchy of Phoenix |publisher=Ststephenbyzantine.org |accessdate=2014-04-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120430202217/http://www.ststephenbyzantine.org/ |archivedate=2012-04-30 }}</ref>\n# [[St. Thomas the Apostle Byzantine Catholic Church]] in Gilbert<ref>[http://www.eparchyofphoenix.org/directory-of-parishes ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110815183654/http://www.eparchyofphoenix.org/directory-of-parishes |date=August 15, 2011 }}</ref>\n# [[Mar Auraha Chaldean and Assyrian Catholic Church]] in Scottsdale<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kaldu.org/2_st_peter_diocese/churches/mar_auraha.htm |title=Mar Auraha Chaldean Church |publisher=Kaldu.org |date= |accessdate=2014-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marauraha.com |title=MarAuraha.com! |publisher=MarAuraha.com! |date= |accessdate=2014-04-01}}</ref>\n# [[St. Joseph Maronite Catholic Church]] in Phoenix<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stjosephaz.org |title=Saint Joseph Maronite Catholic Church Arizona Celebrating Mass According to the Maronite Catholic Rite |publisher=Stjosephaz.org |date= |accessdate=2014-04-01}}</ref>\n# [[St. John of the Desert Melkite Catholic Church]] in Phoenix<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stjohnofthedesert.com |title=Home |publisher=Stjohnofthedesert.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-01}}</ref>\n# [[Dormition of the Mother of God Ukrainian Catholic Church]] in Phoenix<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukrainianchurch.org |title=Dormition of the Mother of God |publisher=Ukrainianchurch.org |date= |accessdate=2014-04-01}}</ref>\n# [[Syro Malabar Catholic Mission]] in Phoenix\n\n== Education ==\nThere are seven Catholic high-schools within the Diocese of Phoenix, 29 elementary schools, and 29 pre-schools.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dphx.org/about/|title=About the Diocese|publisher=Diocese of Phoenix}}</ref> \n[[Benedictine University]] and the [[University of Mary]] offer degree programs within the Diocese of Phoenix, and the diocese operates campus ministry programs at Newman Centers for four public universities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dphx.org/catholic-schools-universities/catholic-colleges-in-phoenix/|title=Catholic Colleges in Phoenix|publisher=Diocese of Phoenix}}</ref>\n\n==Media==\nThe diocese uses several types of media to fulfill its evangelization efforts:\n\n===Radio ministry===\n\nRadio Family Rosary is a radio ministry of the Diocese of Phoenix founded in 1983. The station begins with a recitation of the [[rosary]] every day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://radiofamilyrosary.com/radiofamilyrosary.html|title=Radio Family Rosary|accessdate=April 23, 2008|publisher=Radio Family Rosary|year=2008|author=Radio Family Rosary|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511143515/http://www.radiofamilyrosary.com/radiofamilyrosary.html|archive-date=May 11, 2008|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> After the rosary the station focus on a particular saint, or a point of catechism is held.  The station was founded by Dorothy Westfall, after a suggestion from a Phoenix parishioner suffering from [[arthritis]].<ref name=\"radio2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicsun.org/2006/oct19/media/radiorosary.html|title=The Catholic Sun Newspaper- Group provides rosary, catechism on AM radio|accessdate=April 23, 2008|publisher=The Catholic Sun Newspaper|year=2007|author=Andrew Junker|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720211523/http://www.catholicsun.org/2006/oct19/media/radiorosary.html|archive-date=July 20, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nBishop Thomas Olmsted often uses radio communication and has a website with information about his \"bishop's hour.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thebishopshour.org/|title=Catholic Podcasts - The Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix|website=thebishopshour.org}}</ref> on [[Immaculate Heart Radio]].\n\nThe diocese began financially supporting En Familia radio [[KIDR]] in 2012 to reach out to those who speak Spanish.\n\n=== Newspaper ===\n\n''[[The Catholic Sun]]'' is the official newspaper of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix.<ref name=\"ABOUT US1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicsun.org/aboutus.html|title=Mission Statement|accessdate=April 23, 2008|publisher=The Catholic Sun Newspaper|year=2008|author=The Catholic Sun Newspaper|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080423013957/http://www.catholicsun.org/aboutus.html|archive-date=2008-04-23|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nThe paper is delivered to more than 115,000 homes in the counties of [[Coconino County, Arizona|Coconino]], [[Maricopa County, Arizona|Maricopa]], [[Mohave County, Arizona|Mohave]],  and [[Yavapai County, Arizona|Yavapai]].<ref name=\"advertising\">{{cite web |url=http://www.catholicsun.org/advertising.html |title=ADVERTISING |accessdate=April 23, 2008 |publisher=The Catholic Sun Newspaper |year=2008 |author=The Catholic Sun Newspaper |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080514201626/http://www.catholicsun.org/advertising.html |archive-date=2008-05-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== Television ===\n\nMass is broadcast live from [[Cathedral of Saints Simon and Jude]] each Sunday morning by [[KAZT]], along with a show immediately following entitled \"Catholics Matter\". The Mass was once on [[KUTP]].<ref name=\"TV MASS MINISTRY\">{{cite web |url=http://www.diocesephoenix.org/events/index.html |title=Upcoming Events |accessdate=April 24, 2008 |publisher=Diocese of Phoenix |year=2008 |author=Diocese of Phoenix |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412212948/http://www.diocesephoenix.org/events/index.html |archive-date=April 12, 2008 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Social media===\nThe diocese has an active presence on YouTube, Flickr, Facebook, Twitter and others and continues to expand its presence online.\n\n==Religious orders active in the diocese==\nAs of 2020, twenty-eight communities of religious men and fifty communities of religious women have a presence in the Diocese of Phoenix.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dphx.org/consecrated-life/communities-religious-men/|title=Communities of religious men|publisher=Diocese of Phoenix}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dphx.org/consecrated-life/communities-of-religious-women/|title=Communities of religious women|publisher=Diocese of Phoenix}}</ref> A diocesan Office for Consecrated Life serves as a guide for members of religious communities and for persons interested in consecrated life in its various forms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dphx.org/consecrated-life/|title=Office for Consecrated Life|publisher=Diocese of Phoenix}}</ref>\n\n==Other Catholic organizations in the Diocese of Phoenix==\nThis list is fairly complete, but there might be others to add.\n* [[Andre House]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andrehouse.org|title=Andr\u00e9 House of Arizona \u2013 A House of Hospitality|website=www.andrehouse.org}}</ref>\n* [[Arizona Catholic]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arizonacatholic.org|title=Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix, Arizona - 2018 - The Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix|website=www.arizonacatholic.org}}</ref>\n* [[Arizona Catholic Conference]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120331122523/http://69.50.197.44/acc/]</ref>\n* [[Arizona Rosary Celebration]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rosarysunday.org|title=DOMAIN ERROR|website=rosarysunday.org}}</ref>\n* [[Beginning Experience]] Arizona Chapter<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.azbe.org/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-09-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111003055223/http://www.azbe.org/ |archive-date=2011-10-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Catholic Cemeteries and Mortuaries]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholiccemeteriesphx.com |title=Catholic Cemeteries and Funeral Homes :: Diocese of Phoenix |publisher=Catholiccemeteriesphx.com |date= |accessdate=2018-07-25}}</ref>\n* [[Catholic Commerce Networking Association of Arizona]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ccnaaz.org/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-08-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807131349/http://ccnaaz.org/ |archive-date=2011-08-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Catholic Community Foundation]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ccfphx.org|title=Catholic Community Foundation, Phoenix, AZ|publisher=}}</ref>  In November 2011, the Catholic Community Foundation of Phoenix announced that it was giving [[Thomas J. O'Brien (bishop)|former Bishop Thomas J. O'Brien]] its faith honoree award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/members/Blog/EJMontini/148981|title=azcentral.com - members|website=www.azcentral.com}}</ref>  When news of the intended award became public, there was outrage that the Foundation would honor a bishop who had resigned in disgrace, had admitted involvement in the sexual abuse scandal, and who had been convicted of the felony of hit-and-run involving death.  A few days later, O'Brien declined the award, and Foundation, stating that it did not anticipate the adverse public reaction, issued a formal written apology to the community.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/news/articles/2011/11/23/20111123bishop-obrien-forgoes-catholic-award.html|title=Former Bishop Thomas O'Brien forgoes Catholic award|publisher=}}</ref>\n* [[Catholic Charities Community Services]] \n* [[Catholic Charities Parish and Community Engagement]] /ParishCommunityEngagement.aspx\n* [[Catholic Committee on Scouting]] http://www.phxdccs.org/\n* [[Catholic Education Arizona]], formerly known as [[Catholic Tuition Organization of the Diocese of Phoenix]] http://www.ctodp.org/, http://www.catholiceducationarizona.org/\n* [[Catholic Engaged Encounter]] of Arizona, http://www.arizonacee.org/\n* [[Catholic Mens Fellowship Phoenix]] http://www.cmfp.org/\n* [[Catholic Physicians Guild of Phoenix]]  http://cpgphoenix.com/\n* [[Catholic Renewal Ministries of Phoenix]]  https://web.archive.org/web/20081120032340/http://crm-phoenix.communityspice.com/content\n* [[Catholic Singles Ministry]] http://www.catholicsinglesministry.org\n* [[Cursillo Movement]] in Phoenix http://phoenixcursillo.com/\n* [[Diocese of Phoenix Department of Medical Ethics]], https://web.archive.org/web/20110827174744/http://www.staphx.org/ethics_site/\n* [[Diocese of Phoenix Office of Natural Family Planning]], http://www.phxnfp.org/\n* [[Filipino Catholic Community of Arizona]], http://www.fccaz.com/\n* [[Foundation for Senior Living]] http://www.fsl.org/\n* [[Franciscan Renewal Center]] http://www.thecasa.org/\n* [[Immaculate Heart Radio]]  http://ihradio.com/stations/arizona-stations/phoenix-az-1310-am/\n* [[Italian Catholic Federation]] http://www.icf.org/\n* [[John Paul II Resource Center for the Theology of the Body]]  http://69.50.197.44/mfrl/jp2.html{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} \n* [[Kino Institute]] for Catholic Adult Faith Formation and Leadership, http://www.kinoinstitute.org/\n* [[Knights of Columbus]] Arizona State Council http://www.azknightsofcolumbus.com/\n* [[Korean Catholic Community of Phoenix]], https://web.archive.org/web/20110923002253/http://www.phoenixkoreancatholic.org/\n* [[Legatus]] of Phoenix,  http://www.legatus.org/chapter/phoenix\n* [[Legion of Mary]] of the Diocese of Phoenix, https://legionofmaryphoenix.com/\n* [[Life Teen]] for Catholic Teens http://www.lifeteen.com/\n* [[Living Waters Retreat Center]], Cornville http://www.livingwaterretreatcenter.com/\n* [[Pax Christi]] is active in several locations in the diocese\n* [[Mount Claret Retreat Center]] http://mtclaret.org/\n* [[Phoenix Diocesan Council of Catholic Women]] http://pdccw.com/\n* [[Radio Family Rosary]], http://www.radiofamilyrosary.com/\n* [[St. Joseph's Youth Camp]] http://www.sjycaz.com/\n* [[St. Joseph the Worker]] job service http://www.sjwjobs.org/\n* [[St. Mary's Food Bank Alliance]],  http://www.firstfoodbank.org\n* [[St. Thomas More Society]] of Phoenix, http://stthomasmorephoenix.grou.ps/\n* [[St. Vincent de Paul Society]], Phoenix http://www.stvincentdepaul.net/\n* [[Serra International]] apostolate for vocations, Phoenix Serra Club https://web.archive.org/web/20110923002510/http://www.phoenixserraclub.org/\n* [[Tepeyac Life Teen Camp]], [[Life Teen]], https://web.archive.org/web/20111117025418/http://www.lifeteencamps.com/tepeyac.asp\n* [[World Apostolate of Fatima]]  http://www.wafusa.org/\n* [[Worldwide Marriage Encounter]] Arizona Chapter http://www.wwme-phx.org/\n* [[Youth Arise North America]]  http://www.youtharise.org\n\n==Events since 2000==\nIn 2009 the Diocese contributed $50,000 to the successful campaign by Stand For Marriage Maine to overturn an impending legalization of same-sex civil marriage in Maine.<ref>{{cite news | title =Dioceses major contributors to repeal same-sex marriage | first = Chuck | last = Colbert | url = http://ncronline.org/news/politics/dioceses-major-contributors-repeal-same-sex-marriage | newspaper = [[National Catholic Reporter]] | location = Kansas City, Mo. | date = November 25, 2009 | accessdate =November 29, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mainecampaignfinance.com/public/entity_financial_transactions.asp?TYPE=BQC&ID=4528|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120911203857/http://www.mainecampaignfinance.com/public/entity_financial_transactions.asp?TYPE=BQC&ID=4528|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-09-11|title=Maine Campaign Finance contributions}}</ref>\n\nOn June 11, 2014, the diocese was \"stunned and deeply saddened\" at an attack on two priests during a burglary at Mater Misericordiae Mission in Phoenix. Parochial vicar Rev. Kenneth Walker, [[Priestly Fraternity of St. Peter|FSSP]], 28, ordained a priest just two years, was fatally shot. Rev. Joseph Terra, [[Priestly Fraternity of St. Peter|FSSP]], was wounded.<ref name=\"PriestKilled\">{{cite news|title=28-year-old priest killed in Phoenix church burglary|url=http://www.phoenixherald.com/index.php/sid/222852679/scat/caf48823f1822eb3/ht/28-year-old-priest-killed-in-Phoenix-church-burglary|accessdate=June 12, 2014|publisher=Phoenix Herald}}</ref>\n\nOn August 4 2017, it was announced that a civil lawsuit was filed against [[Thomas J. O'Brien (bishop)|Thomas J. O'Brien]], who served as Bishop of the Catholic Diocese of Phoenix between the years 1982 to 2003,<ref name=\"o'Brinava\">https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/arizona/articles/2017-08-03/ex-catholic-bishop-of-phoenix-accused-of-sex-abuse-of-boy</ref> O'Brien is accused of sexually molested a boy on several occasions at parishes in Phoenix and Goodyear from 1977 to 1982.<ref name=\"o'Brinava\" /> O'Brien died on August 26, 2018, following complications from Parkinson's Disease.<ref>http://www.catholicsun.org/2018/08/27/bishop-thomas-j-obrien-retired-bishop-of-phoenix-dies-at-82/</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, Joseph J. Henn, a former priest, was extradited from Italy to face charges of molestation in Phoenix. He had been laicized and expelled from the [[Salvatorian]] order in 2006.<ref name=phoenixdefrocking>https://cruxnow.com/church-in-europe/2019/05/31/former-priest-wanted-on-abuse-charges-in-arizona-arrested-in-italy/</ref><ref>https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/phoenix/2019/06/15/ex-priest-joseph-john-henn-returned-az-italy-child-molestation-charges/1467366001/</ref>\n\nOn February 25, 2020, indicted Diocese of Phoenix priest Thomas Spaulding, who was accused of sexually abusing at least two boys in Maricopa County, died awaiting trial.<ref name=spaulding>https://www.azfamily.com/news/phoenix-priest-indicted-on-child-sex-abuse-charges-dead-at/article_e0dc7102-58c6-11ea-9840-5fc30cb13a9c.html</ref><ref name=azcentralspaulding /> Spaulding, who was 75 years old when he died, was charged in January 2020 with six counts of sexual misconduct and one charge of child molestatation.<ref name=spaulding /><ref name=azcentralspaulding>https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/phoenix/2020/02/26/roman-catholic-diocese-phoenix-mesa-priest-john-jack-spaulding-dies-child-sex-crimes/4883112002/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Catholicism}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Catholic Church by country]]\n* [[Catholic Church in the United States]]\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States#Ecclesiastical province of Santa Fe|Ecclesiastical Province of Santa Fe]]\n* [[Global organisation of the Catholic Church]]\n* [[Life Teen]]\n* [[List of Roman Catholic archdioceses]] (by country and continent)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (alphabetical)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (structured view)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States]]\n{{div col end}}\n<!-- please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://dphx.org/ Official site]\n** [https://dphx.org/parishes/ List of parishes]\n** [https://dphx.org/about/related-organizations/ Other Catholic Organizations in the Diocese of Phoenix]\n** [https://dphx.org/bishop-olmsteds-coat-of-arms/ Coat of arms of the bishop and of the diocese]\n** [https://dphx.org/youth-protection/ Office for Child and Youth Protection]\n* [https://www.azcatholicconference.org/ Arizona Catholic Conference]\n* [http://www.thebishopshour.org/ \"Bishop's Hour\" radio program]\n* [http://www.catholiccharitiesaz.org/  Catholic Charities Community Services Arizona]\n* [http://www.catholicsun.org/ \"The Catholic Sun\" newspaper]\n* [http://www.catholicschoolsphx.com/ Catholic Schools of the Diocese of Phoenix]\n* [[United States Conference of Catholic Bishops]]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Santa Fe}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roman Catholic Diocese Of Phoenix}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in the United States|Phoenix]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Santa Fe|Phoenix]]\n[[Category:Catholic Church in Arizona|Diocese of Phoenix]]\n[[Category:Culture of Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Christian organizations established in 1969]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 20th century|Phoenix]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Phoenix"}
{"title_page": "Avery Andon (artist)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Avery Andon\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Art dealer and manager\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = ArtLife\n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Avery Andon''' is an American art dealer and manager based in [[Miami]], Florida. He is notable for managing graffiti artist [[Alec Monopoly]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/graffiti-in-the-living-room-1385594516|title=Graffiti in the Living Room|last=Buerger|first=Megan|date=2013-11-27|work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> throughout most of his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/241227|title=5 Points of Success Entrepreneurs Can Learn From a Masked Street Artist|last=Long|first=Jonathan|date=December 29, 2014|work=Entrepreneur|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAndon began his career as an art collector in [[New York City]] by purchasing local [[street art]].<ref name=\"Artnet\">{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/partner-content/dealer-avery-andon-alec-monopoly|title=9 Questions for Avery Andon, Alec Monopoly\u2019s Dealer and Manager|last=|first=|date=2019-10-10|work=artnet News|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> He later went on to become a manager for various artists, including street artist [[Alec Monopoly]]. He has also negotiated an artist residency between him XS / [[Wynn Hotel]]s. Having managed Alec Monopoly for over 10 years, Andon was responsible for his long-term success as an internationally known street artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/museums/la-et-cm-alec-monopoly-20181102-story.html|title=Street artist Alec Monopoly is a blinged-out, socially engaged paradox|last=Ohanesian|first=Liz|date=Nov 2, 2018|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Andon founded ArtLife,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsbreak.com/news/0ICeKUEL/celebrities-spotted-out-and-about-week-of-november-23rd|title=celebrities Spotted Out and About \u2013 Week of November 23rd|last=|first=|date=2018-11-23|work=News Break|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> a popular online art platform and gallery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chaddscott/2018/10/11/visions-of-south-africa-in-los-angeles-during-lionel-smit-show-at-artlife-gallery/#4062b4932763|title=Visions Of South Africa In Los Angeles During Lionel Smit Show At ArtLife Gallery|last=Scott|first=Chadd|date=2018-10-11|work=Forbes|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/pictures/kourtney-kardashian-has-dinner-with-ex-scott-disick-sofia-richie-pics/|title=Kourtney Kardashian Dines With Ex Scott Disick and His GF Sofia Richie: They \u2018Seemed to Be Getting Along\u2019|last=Briese|first=Nicole|date=November 17, 2018|work=US Magazine|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Artlife Gallery has presented works from [[Andy Warhol]], [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]], [[Keith Haring]], [[Banksy]], and many other artists, with exhibitions held in [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City]], [[Miami]], [[Seoul]], attended by notable celebrities including [[Kim Kardashian]], [[Kourtney Kardashian]], [[Scott Disick]], [[Serena Williams]], and [[Tyga]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.artlife.com/about-us/|title=ArtLife|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://radaronline.com/exclusives/2018/11/scott-disick-relieved-kourtney-kardashian-sophia-richie-dinner/|title=Kourtney Accepts Baby Daddy Scott's Girlfriend Sophia Into Family At Dinner |last=|first=|date=November 19, 2018|publisher=Reality TV online|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pagesix.com/2018/11/19/kourtney-kardashian-and-larsa-pippen-enjoy-a-night-out-and-more-star-snaps/slide-1/|title=Kourtney Kardashian and Larsa Pippen enjoy a night out and more star snaps|last=Bergen|first=Spencer|date=November 19, 2018|publisher=Page Six|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/inside-kourtney-kardashians-dinner-with-ex-scott-disick-and-sofia-richie-114075|title=Inside Kourtney Kardashian's Dinner With Ex Scott Disick and Sofia Richie|last=Drysdale|first=Jennifer|date=November 17, 2018|publisher=ET Online|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nHe is also the co-founder of City Seats, a charity for repurposing [[Yankee Stadium]] seats as artwork to benefit the [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pix11.com/2017/02/23/charitable-exhibit-will-feature-reimagined-vintage-yankee-stadium-seats/|title=Charitable exhibit will feature reimagined vintage Yankee Stadium seats|last=|first=|date=2017-02-23|work=Pix 11|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nAndon also currently serves on the committee of [[WildAid]], an anti-poaching non-profit organization,<ref>[https://wildaid.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/WildAid_Annual-Report-2018_v13.pdf WildAid 2018 Annual Report]</ref> and is highly active in the Los Angeles entertainment scene.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://radaronline.com/exclusives/2018/11/scott-disick-relieved-kourtney-kardashian-sophia-richie-dinner/|title=Kourtney Accepts Baby Daddy Scott's Girlfriend Sophia Into Family At Dinner |last=|first=|date=November 19, 2018|work=Reality TV online|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pagesix.com/2018/11/19/kourtney-kardashian-and-larsa-pippen-enjoy-a-night-out-and-more-star-snaps/slide-1/|title=Kourtney Kardashian and Larsa Pippen enjoy a night out and more star snaps|last=Bergen|first=Spencer|date=November 19, 2018|work=Page Six|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Alec Monopoly]]\n*[[Andy Warhol]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.artlife.com/ ArtLife]\n*[https://www.discogs.com/artist/1902055-Andon-Artists-Inc Andon Artists] on [[Discogs]]\n*[https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/paint-the-town/id1505448867 Paint the Town] podcast\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andon, Avery}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American art dealers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Avery Andon\n| image         = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Art dealer and manager\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = ArtLife\n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Avery Andon''' is an American art dealer and manager based in [[Miami]], Florida. He is notable for managing graffiti artist [[Alec Monopoly]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/graffiti-in-the-living-room-1385594516|title=Graffiti in the Living Room|last=Buerger|first=Megan|date=2013-11-27|work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> throughout most of his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/241227|title=5 Points of Success Entrepreneurs Can Learn From a Masked Street Artist|last=Long|first=Jonathan|date=December 29, 2014|work=Entrepreneur|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAndon began his career as an art collector in [[New York City]] by purchasing local [[street art]].<ref name=\"Artnet\">{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/partner-content/dealer-avery-andon-alec-monopoly|title=9 Questions for Avery Andon, Alec Monopoly\u2019s Dealer and Manager|last=|first=|date=2019-10-10|work=artnet News|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> He later went on to become a manager for various artists, including street artist [[Alec Monopoly]]. He has also negotiated an artist residency between him XS / [[Wynn Hotel]]s. Having managed Alec Monopoly for over 10 years, Andon was responsible for his long-term success as an internationally known street artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/arts/museums/la-et-cm-alec-monopoly-20181102-story.html|title=Street artist Alec Monopoly is a blinged-out, socially engaged paradox|last=Ohanesian|first=Liz|date=Nov 2, 2018|work=The Los Angeles Times|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Andon founded ArtLife,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsbreak.com/news/0ICeKUEL/celebrities-spotted-out-and-about-week-of-november-23rd|title=celebrities Spotted Out and About \u2013 Week of November 23rd|last=|first=|date=2018-11-23|work=News Break|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> a popular online art platform and gallery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chaddscott/2018/10/11/visions-of-south-africa-in-los-angeles-during-lionel-smit-show-at-artlife-gallery/#4062b4932763|title=Visions Of South Africa In Los Angeles During Lionel Smit Show At ArtLife Gallery|last=Scott|first=Chadd|date=2018-10-11|work=Forbes|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/pictures/kourtney-kardashian-has-dinner-with-ex-scott-disick-sofia-richie-pics/|title=Kourtney Kardashian Dines With Ex Scott Disick and His GF Sofia Richie: They \u2018Seemed to Be Getting Along\u2019|last=Briese|first=Nicole|date=November 17, 2018|work=US Magazine|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Artlife Gallery has presented works from [[Andy Warhol]], [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]], [[Keith Haring]], [[Banksy]], and many other artists, with exhibitions held in [[Los Angeles]], [[New York City]], [[Miami]], [[Seoul]], attended by notable celebrities including [[Kim Kardashian]], [[Kourtney Kardashian]], [[Scott Disick]], [[Serena Williams]], and [[Tyga]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.artlife.com/about-us/|title=ArtLife|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://radaronline.com/exclusives/2018/11/scott-disick-relieved-kourtney-kardashian-sophia-richie-dinner/|title=Kourtney Accepts Baby Daddy Scott's Girlfriend Sophia Into Family At Dinner |last=|first=|date=November 19, 2018|publisher=Reality TV online|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pagesix.com/2018/11/19/kourtney-kardashian-and-larsa-pippen-enjoy-a-night-out-and-more-star-snaps/slide-1/|title=Kourtney Kardashian and Larsa Pippen enjoy a night out and more star snaps|last=Bergen|first=Spencer|date=November 19, 2018|publisher=Page Six|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/inside-kourtney-kardashians-dinner-with-ex-scott-disick-and-sofia-richie-114075|title=Inside Kourtney Kardashian's Dinner With Ex Scott Disick and Sofia Richie|last=Drysdale|first=Jennifer|date=November 17, 2018|publisher=ET Online|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nHe is also the co-founder of City Seats, a charity for repurposing [[Yankee Stadium]] seats as artwork to benefit The [[Boys & Girls Club of America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pix11.com/2017/02/23/charitable-exhibit-will-feature-reimagined-vintage-yankee-stadium-seats/|title=Charitable exhibit will feature reimagined vintage Yankee Stadium seats|last=|first=|date=2017-02-23|work=Pix 11|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nAndon also currently serves on the committee of [[WildAid]], an anti-poaching non-profit organization,<ref>[https://wildaid.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/WildAid_Annual-Report-2018_v13.pdf WildAid 2018 Annual Report]</ref> and is highly active in the Los Angeles entertainment scene.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://radaronline.com/exclusives/2018/11/scott-disick-relieved-kourtney-kardashian-sophia-richie-dinner/|title=Kourtney Accepts Baby Daddy Scott's Girlfriend Sophia Into Family At Dinner |last=|first=|date=November 19, 2018|work=Reality TV online|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pagesix.com/2018/11/19/kourtney-kardashian-and-larsa-pippen-enjoy-a-night-out-and-more-star-snaps/slide-1/|title=Kourtney Kardashian and Larsa Pippen enjoy a night out and more star snaps|last=Bergen|first=Spencer|date=November 19, 2018|work=Page Six|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Alec Monopoly]]\n*[[Andy Warhol]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.artlife.com/ ArtLife]\n*[https://www.discogs.com/artist/1902055-Andon-Artists-Inc Andon Artists] on [[Discogs]]\n*[https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/paint-the-town/id1505448867 Paint the Town] podcast\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andon, Avery}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American art dealers]]\n", "name_user": "Mandarax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correct name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avery_Andon_(artist)"}
{"title_page": "Maria Corti", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Maria Corti\n| image       = Maria Corti.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1915|09|07|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Milan]], Italy\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2002|02|22|1915|09|07|df=yes}} \n| death_place = Milan, Italy\n| nationality = Italian\n| occupation  = Literary scholar and novelist\n}}\n'''Maria Corti''' (7 September 1915 \u2013 22 February 2002) was an Italian [[philologist]], literary critic, and novelist. Considered one of the leading literary scholars of post-World War II Italy, she was awarded numerous prizes including the [[Premio Campiello]] for the entire body of her work. Her works of fiction were informed by her literary scholarship but also had a distinctly autobiographical vein, particularly her ''Voci del nord-est'' (1986) and ''II canto delle sirene'' (1989). For most of her career she was based at the [[University of Pavia]] where she established the ''Fondo Manoscritti di Autori Moderni e Contemporanei'', an extensive curated archive of material on modern Italian writers.<ref name = \"West\">West, Rebecca (2006). [https://books.google.com/books?id=d9NcAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA513 \"Maria Corti (1915\u20132002)\"]. ''Encyclopedia of Italian Literary Studies'', pp. 513-515. Routledge. {{ISBN|1135455309}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n\nCorti was born in Milan, the only child of Emilio and Celestina (''n\u00e9e'' Goldoni) Corti. Her mother was a pianist who died when Corti was ten years old. After her mother's death, her father, an engineer frequently absent from Milan while working in southern Italy, placed her in a boarding school run by the Sisters of [[Saint Marcellina]]. She would remain there for the next five years. After leaving the boarding school she studied at a [[liceo]] in Milan, living largely on her own apart from summer holidays spent with her father in [[Apulia]]. She then attended the [[University of Milan]] where she would eventually complete two [[laurea]] degrees. The first was in literature in 1936 with a thesis on medieval Latin supervised by [[Benvenuto Terracini]]. The second was in philosophy with a thesis on [[African Spir]] supervised by [[Antonio Banfi]].<ref name = \"RAI\" /><ref name= \"DBI\">Montagnani, Cristina (2013). [http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/maria-corti_%28Dizionario-Biografico%29/ \"Corti, Maria\"]. ''[[Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani ]]''. Online version Retrieved 23 October 2014 {{in lang|it}}.</ref>\n\nCorti's early academic career coincided with [[Italian Fascism]] and was curtailed by laws which prohibited women from holding university or liceo teaching positions. From 1939 to 1950 she worked as a teacher in a [[Gymnasium (school)#Italy|ginnasio]] (secondary school for students from age 11 to 16) in Brescia, dedicated herself to private study and writing, and was active in anti-Fascist circles. From 1950 until 1962 she taught at the Alessandro Volta liceo in Como and then at the Cesare Beccaria liceo in Milan. She also held a part-time teaching post at the [[University of Pavia]] from 1955 which she combined with her teaching at the liceo in Milan. After her mentor Benvenuto Terracini had returned from exile in 1947, she renewed her research collaboration with him and formed close personal and intellectual ties with his other students\u2014[[Cesare Segre]], [[Gian Luigi Beccaria]] and [[Bice Mortara Garavelli]]. The ties would last a lifetime, and Corti (who never married) very often spoke of these scholars as her \"family\".<ref name= \"DBI\" /><ref name = \"Segre1\">[[Cesare Segre|Segre, Cesare]] (24 February 2002). [http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2002/febbraio/24/MARIA_CORTI_ragazza_che_innamoro_co_0_0202245519.shtml \"Maria Corti\" La ragazza che si innamor\u00f2 di Dante\"]. ''[[Corriere della Sera]]''. Retrieved 6 November 2014 {{in lang|it}}.</ref>\n\nHer first major university post came in 1962 when she was appointed to the chair of Italian language history at the [[University of Lecce]]. That same year she published her first work of fiction, ''L'ora di tutti'', an historical novel set in [[Otranto]]. She had written two other novels in 1947. The first of these, originally titled ''Il treno della pazienza'' and based on her experiences commuting by train between her teaching job in Brescia and her home in Milan, was published in a revised version in 1981 as ''Cantare al buio''. The second, ''La leggenda di domani'', was published posthumously in 2007 with an introduction by Cesare Segre. Set in Apulia, the novel tells the story of a young orphan girl from Milan who seeks refuge with a fisherman's family in [[Santa Maria di Leuca]].<ref name = \"West\"/><ref>Vacca, Nicola (11 May 2007). [http://www.mannieditori.it/rassegna/maria-corti-la-leggenda-di-domani-3 \"E nel Salento magico sbocci\u00f2 una scrittrice\"]. ''[[Secolo d'Italia]]'' (reprinted by Manni Editori). Retrieved 6 November 2014 {{in lang|it}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1964, Corti returned to the University of Pavia, where she was given a permanent appointment as a professor of Italian Language History. She remained at Pavia for the rest of her career where her scholarship, along with that of Cesare Segre, D'Arco Silvio Avalle, and Dante Isella, Corti's scholarship created the so-called \"Pavia school\" of philology and [[semiotics]]. At Pavia, she also established the ''Fondo Manoscritti di Autori Moderni e Contemporanei'', an extensive curated archive of autograph manuscripts and other documents by 19th- and 20th-century Italian writers. She founded and edited the journal ''Autografo'' which published scholarly work based on material in the archive, as well as two other journals ''[[Alfabeta]]'' and ''Strumenti critici''.<ref name = \"West\"/>\n\nCorti continued working up until the time of her death. The manuscript of her last work, ''Scritti su Cavalcanti e Dante'', was handed to her publisher in early February 2002. She died of respiratory failure in Milan two weeks later at the age of 86.<ref name=\"RAI\">[[Rai News]] (23 February 2002). [http://www.rainews.it/it/news.php?newsid=18390 \"E' morta la scrittrice Maria Corti\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106160002/http://www.rainews.it/it/news.php?newsid=18390 |date=2014-11-06 }}. Retrieved 28 October 2014 {{in lang|it}}</ref> Her funeral was held at the University of Pavia attended by her colleagues and students, [[Umberto Eco]], and the presidents of the [[Accademia della Crusca]] and the [[Accademia dei Lincei]]. Following the funeral, she was buried in her maternal family tomb in [[Pellio Intelvi]]. Volume 44 of ''Autografo'', dedicated entirely to Corti's life and work and including previously unpublished pages from her diary, was published later that year.<ref>''[[Corriere della Sera]]'' (26 February 2002). [http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2002/febbraio/26/ADDIO_MARIA_CORTI_co_5_0202263806.shtml \"L'addio a Maria Corti\"] Retrieved 6 November 2014 {{in lang|it}}.</ref><ref>Cremante, Renzo and Stella, Angelo (eds.) (2002). ''Maria Corti: Congedi primi e ultimi'' (''Autografo'', Vol. 44). Interlinea</ref>\n\n==Principal works==\n'''Philology and literary criticism'''\n* ''Studi sulla latiniti\u00e0 merovingia in testi agiografici minori'' (Principato, 1939)\n* ''Studi sulla sintassi della lingua poetica avanti lo Stilnovo'' (Olschki 1953)\n* ''Metodi e fantasmi'' (Feltrinelli, 1969), republished in 1997 in an expanded edition under the title ''Nuovi metodi e fantasmi''\n* ''I metodi attuali della critica in Italia'', co-authored with [[Cesare Segre]] (ERI, 1970)\n* ''Entro dipinta gabbia: Tutti gli scritti inediti, rari e editi 1809-1810 di Giacomo Leopardi'', (Bompiani, 1972)\n* ''Princ\u00ecpi della comunicazione letteraria'' (Bompiani, 1976), published in English translation as ''An Introduction to Literary Semiotics'' (Indiana University Press, 1978)\n* ''II viaggio testuale. Le ideologie e le strutture semiotiche'' (Einaudi, 1978)\n* ''Beppe Fenoglio. Storia di un \u00abcontinuum\u00bb narrativo'' (Liviana, 1978)\n* ''Una lingua di tutti: Pratica, storia e grammatica della lingua italiana'', co-authored with Emilio Manzotti and Flavia Ravazzoli (Le Monnier, 1979)\n* ''Dante a un nuovo crocevia'' (Sansoni-Le lettere, 1981)\n* ''La felicit\u00e0 mentale: Nuove prospettive per Cavalcanti e Dante'' (Einaudi, 1983) \n* ''Per filo e per segno: Grammatica italiana per il biennio'', co-authored with Claudia Caffi (Bompiani, 1989)\n* ''Storia della lingua italiana e storia dei testi'' (Ricciardi, 1989)\n* ''Percorsi dell'invenzione: Il linguaggio poetico e Dante'' (Einaudi, 1993)\n* ''Ombre dal fondo'' (Einaudi, 1997)\n* ''Un ponte tra latino e italiano'' (Interlinea, 2002)\n* ''Scritti su Cavalcanti e Dante'' (Einaudi, 2003)\n\n'''Fiction'''\n* ''L'ora di tutti'' (Feltrinelli, 1962)\n* ''II ballo dei sapienti'' (Mondadori, 1966)\n* ''Cantare nel buio'' (Farfengo, 1981)\n* ''Voci del nord-est: Taccuino americano'' (Bompiani, 1986)\n* ''II canto delle sirene'' (Bompiani, 1989)\n* ''Otranto allo specchio'', (All'insegna del pesce d'oro, 1990)\n* ''Catasto magico'' (Einaudi, 1999)\n* ''Storie'' (Manni, 2000)\n* ''Le pietre verbali'' (Einaudi, 2001)\n* ''La leggenda di domani'' (Manni, 2007)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Nesi, Cristina (1995). ''Dialogo in pubblico'' (book-length interview with Maria Corti). Rizzoli. {{OCLC|456120449}}\n*Guerra, Giorgia and Nesi, Cristina (eds.) (2000). '' Maria Corti: Voci, canti e catasti''. Interlinea. {{OCLC|248628834}}\n*Cremante, Renzo and Stella, Angelo (eds.) (2002). ''Maria Corti: Congedi primi e ultimi''. Interlinea. {{OCLC|51772998}}\n*Scorrano,  Luigi (2002) ''Carte inquiete: Maria Corti, Biagia Marniti, Antonia Pozzi''. Longo. {{OCLC|470210638}}\n*Dolfi, Anna (ed.) (2005). ''Testimonianze per Maria Corti''. Bulzoni {{OCLC|255133910}}\n*Grignani, Maria Antonietta and Stella, Angelo (eds.) (2012). ''Maria Corti: Ancora dialogando''. Interlinea. {{OCLC|800000731}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corti, Maria}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian women novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian women writers]]\n[[Category:Italian philologists]]\n[[Category:Women philologists]]\n[[Category:People from Milan]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian novelists]]\n[[Category:University of Milan alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pavia faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Salento faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Maria Corti\n| image       = Maria Corti.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1915|09|07|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Milan]], Italy\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|2002|02|22|1915|09|07|df=yes}} \n| death_place = Milan, Italy\n| nationality = Italian\n| occupation  = Literary scholar and novelist\n}}\n'''Maria Corti''' (7 September 1915 \u2013 22 February 2002) was an Italian [[philologist]], literary critic, and novelist. Considered one of the leading literary scholars of post-World War II Italy, she was awarded numerous prizes including the [[Premio Campiello]] for the entire body of her work. Her works of fiction were informed by her literary scholarship but also had a distinctly autobiographical vein, particularly her ''Voci del nord-est'' (1986) and ''II canto delle sirene'' (1989). For most of her career she was based at the [[University of Pavia]] where she established the ''Fondo Manoscritti di Autori Moderni e Contemporanei'', an extensive curated archive of material on modern Italian writers.<ref name = \"West\">West, Rebecca (2006). [https://books.google.com/books?id=d9NcAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA513 \"Maria Corti (1915\u20132002)\"]. ''Encyclopedia of Italian Literary Studies'', pp. 513-515. Routledge. {{ISBN|1135455309}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n\nCorti was born in Milan, the only child of Emilio and Celestina (''n\u00e9e'' Goldoni) Corti. Her mother was a pianist who died when Corti was ten years old. After her mother's death, her father, an engineer frequently absent from Milan while working in southern Italy, placed her in a boarding school run by the Sisters of [[Saint Marcellina]]. She would remain there for the next five years. After leaving the boarding school she studied at a [[liceo]] in Milan, living largely on her own apart from summer holidays spent with her father in [[Apulia]]. She then attended the [[University of Milan]] where she would eventually complete two [[laurea]] degrees. The first was in literature in 1936 with a thesis on medieval Latin supervised by [[Benvenuto Terracini]]. The second was in philosophy with a thesis on [[African Spir]] supervised by [[Antonio Banfi]].<ref name = \"RAI\" /><ref name= \"DBI\">Montagnani, Cristina (2013). [http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/maria-corti_%28Dizionario-Biografico%29/ \"Corti, Maria\"]. ''[[Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani ]]''. Online version Retrieved 23 October 2014 {{in lang|it}}.</ref>\n\nCorti's early academic career coincided with [[Italian Fascism]] and was curtailed by laws which prohibited women from holding university or liceo teaching positions. From 1939 to 1950 she worked as a teacher in a [[Gymnasium (school)#Italy|ginnasio]] (secondary school for students from age 11 to 16) in Brescia, dedicated herself to private study and writing, and was active in anti-Fascist circles. From 1950 until 1962 she taught at the Alessandro Volta liceo in Como and then at the Cesare Beccaria liceo in Milan. She also held a part-time teaching post at the [[University of Pavia]] from 1955 which she combined with her teaching at the liceo in Milan. After her mentor Benvenuto Terracini had returned from exile in 1947, she renewed her research collaboration with him and formed close personal and intellectual ties with his other students\u2014[[Cesare Segre]], [[Gian Luigi Beccaria]] and [[Bice Mortara Garavelli]]. The ties would last a lifetime, and Corti (who never married) and often spoke of these scholars as her \"family\".<ref name= \"DBI\" /><ref name = \"Segre1\">[[Cesare Segre|Segre, Cesare]] (24 February 2002). [http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2002/febbraio/24/MARIA_CORTI_ragazza_che_innamoro_co_0_0202245519.shtml \"Maria Corti\" La ragazza che si innamor\u00f2 di Dante\"]. ''[[Corriere della Sera]]''. Retrieved 6 November 2014 {{in lang|it}}.</ref>\n\nHer first major university post came in 1962 when she was appointed to the chair of Italian language history at the [[University of Lecce]]. That same year she published her first work of fiction, ''L'ora di tutti'', an historical novel set in [[Otranto]]. She had written two other novels in 1947. The first of these, originally titled ''Il treno della pazienza'' and based on her experiences commuting by train between her teaching job in Brescia and her home in Milan, was published in a revised version in 1981 as ''Cantare al buio''. The second, ''La leggenda di domani'', was published posthumously in 2007 with an introduction by Cesare Segre. Set in Apulia, the novel tells the story of a young orphan girl from Milan who seeks refuge with a fisherman's family in [[Santa Maria di Leuca]].<ref name = \"West\"/><ref>Vacca, Nicola (11 May 2007). [http://www.mannieditori.it/rassegna/maria-corti-la-leggenda-di-domani-3 \"E nel Salento magico sbocci\u00f2 una scrittrice\"]. ''[[Secolo d'Italia]]'' (reprinted by Manni Editori). Retrieved 6 November 2014 {{in lang|it}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1964, Corti returned to the University of Pavia, where she was given a permanent appointment as a professor of Italian Language History. She remained at Pavia for the rest of her career where her scholarship, along with that of Cesare Segre, D'Arco Silvio Avalle, and Dante Isella, Corti's scholarship created the so-called \"Pavia school\" of philology and [[semiotics]]. At Pavia, she also established the ''Fondo Manoscritti di Autori Moderni e Contemporanei'', an extensive curated archive of autograph manuscripts and other documents by 19th- and 20th-century Italian writers. She founded and edited the journal ''Autografo'' which published scholarly work based on material in the archive, as well as two other journals ''[[Alfabeta]]'' and ''Strumenti critici''.<ref name = \"West\"/>\n\nCorti continued working up until the time of her death. The manuscript of her last work, ''Scritti su Cavalcanti e Dante'', was handed to her publisher in early February 2002. She died of respiratory failure in Milan two weeks later at the age of 86.<ref name=\"RAI\">[[Rai News]] (23 February 2002). [http://www.rainews.it/it/news.php?newsid=18390 \"E' morta la scrittrice Maria Corti\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106160002/http://www.rainews.it/it/news.php?newsid=18390 |date=2014-11-06 }}. Retrieved 28 October 2014 {{in lang|it}}</ref> Her funeral was held at the University of Pavia attended by her colleagues and students, [[Umberto Eco]], and the presidents of the [[Accademia della Crusca]] and the [[Accademia dei Lincei]]. Following the funeral, she was buried in her maternal family tomb in [[Pellio Intelvi]]. Volume 44 of ''Autografo'', dedicated entirely to Corti's life and work and including previously unpublished pages from her diary, was published later that year.<ref>''[[Corriere della Sera]]'' (26 February 2002). [http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2002/febbraio/26/ADDIO_MARIA_CORTI_co_5_0202263806.shtml \"L'addio a Maria Corti\"] Retrieved 6 November 2014 {{in lang|it}}.</ref><ref>Cremante, Renzo and Stella, Angelo (eds.) (2002). ''Maria Corti: Congedi primi e ultimi'' (''Autografo'', Vol. 44). Interlinea</ref>\n\n==Principal works==\n'''Philology and literary criticism'''\n* ''Studi sulla latiniti\u00e0 merovingia in testi agiografici minori'' (Principato, 1939)\n* ''Studi sulla sintassi della lingua poetica avanti lo Stilnovo'' (Olschki 1953)\n* ''Metodi e fantasmi'' (Feltrinelli, 1969), republished in 1997 in an expanded edition under the title ''Nuovi metodi e fantasmi''\n* ''I metodi attuali della critica in Italia'', co-authored with [[Cesare Segre]] (ERI, 1970)\n* ''Entro dipinta gabbia: Tutti gli scritti inediti, rari e editi 1809-1810 di Giacomo Leopardi'', (Bompiani, 1972)\n* ''Princ\u00ecpi della comunicazione letteraria'' (Bompiani, 1976), published in English translation as ''An Introduction to Literary Semiotics'' (Indiana University Press, 1978)\n* ''II viaggio testuale. Le ideologie e le strutture semiotiche'' (Einaudi, 1978)\n* ''Beppe Fenoglio. Storia di un \u00abcontinuum\u00bb narrativo'' (Liviana, 1978)\n* ''Una lingua di tutti: Pratica, storia e grammatica della lingua italiana'', co-authored with Emilio Manzotti and Flavia Ravazzoli (Le Monnier, 1979)\n* ''Dante a un nuovo crocevia'' (Sansoni-Le lettere, 1981)\n* ''La felicit\u00e0 mentale: Nuove prospettive per Cavalcanti e Dante'' (Einaudi, 1983) \n* ''Per filo e per segno: Grammatica italiana per il biennio'', co-authored with Claudia Caffi (Bompiani, 1989)\n* ''Storia della lingua italiana e storia dei testi'' (Ricciardi, 1989)\n* ''Percorsi dell'invenzione: Il linguaggio poetico e Dante'' (Einaudi, 1993)\n* ''Ombre dal fondo'' (Einaudi, 1997)\n* ''Un ponte tra latino e italiano'' (Interlinea, 2002)\n* ''Scritti su Cavalcanti e Dante'' (Einaudi, 2003)\n\n'''Fiction'''\n* ''L'ora di tutti'' (Feltrinelli, 1962)\n* ''II ballo dei sapienti'' (Mondadori, 1966)\n* ''Cantare nel buio'' (Farfengo, 1981)\n* ''Voci del nord-est: Taccuino americano'' (Bompiani, 1986)\n* ''II canto delle sirene'' (Bompiani, 1989)\n* ''Otranto allo specchio'', (All'insegna del pesce d'oro, 1990)\n* ''Catasto magico'' (Einaudi, 1999)\n* ''Storie'' (Manni, 2000)\n* ''Le pietre verbali'' (Einaudi, 2001)\n* ''La leggenda di domani'' (Manni, 2007)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Nesi, Cristina (1995). ''Dialogo in pubblico'' (book-length interview with Maria Corti). Rizzoli. {{OCLC|456120449}}\n*Guerra, Giorgia and Nesi, Cristina (eds.) (2000). '' Maria Corti: Voci, canti e catasti''. Interlinea. {{OCLC|248628834}}\n*Cremante, Renzo and Stella, Angelo (eds.) (2002). ''Maria Corti: Congedi primi e ultimi''. Interlinea. {{OCLC|51772998}}\n*Scorrano,  Luigi (2002) ''Carte inquiete: Maria Corti, Biagia Marniti, Antonia Pozzi''. Longo. {{OCLC|470210638}}\n*Dolfi, Anna (ed.) (2005). ''Testimonianze per Maria Corti''. Bulzoni {{OCLC|255133910}}\n*Grignani, Maria Antonietta and Stella, Angelo (eds.) (2012). ''Maria Corti: Ancora dialogando''. Interlinea. {{OCLC|800000731}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corti, Maria}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:Italian women novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian women writers]]\n[[Category:Italian philologists]]\n[[Category:Women philologists]]\n[[Category:People from Milan]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian novelists]]\n[[Category:University of Milan alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Pavia faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Salento faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Teo Orlando", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife and career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maria_Corti"}
